16
00:00:36,230 --> 00:00:40,030
Sync and corrections by atrn97g
for www.addic7ed.com

17
00:00:40,120 --> 00:00:43,589
Jane: A relationship
is like open-heart surgery.

18
00:00:43,624 --> 00:00:45,291
It's all about exposure.

19
00:00:45,326 --> 00:00:47,894
Your fears are exposed.

20
00:00:47,928 --> 00:00:49,095
Your heart is exposed.

21
00:00:49,129 --> 00:00:51,831
And they put you in a gown
that exposures your...

22
00:00:51,865 --> 00:00:54,267
well, anyway, the metaphor isn't perfect.

23
00:00:54,301 --> 00:00:55,501
The point is,

24
00:00:55,536 --> 00:00:58,104
what's important is that
you have complete confidence

25
00:00:58,138 --> 00:01:00,206
in the person who will
hold your heart in his hands.

26
00:01:00,240 --> 00:01:01,341
[ Monitor beeping ]

27
00:01:01,375 --> 00:01:02,775
I don't want you to worry
about a thing, Jane.

28
00:01:02,810 --> 00:01:05,311
Owen? Are you a doctor?

29
00:01:05,346 --> 00:01:07,580
Just close your eyes and relax, Jane.

30
00:01:07,614 --> 00:01:09,315
Grayson, what are you...
what are you doing?

31
00:01:09,350 --> 00:01:10,383
What are you doing?

32
00:01:10,417 --> 00:01:12,051
- She's my patient.
- I don't think so.

33
00:01:12,086 --> 00:01:13,152
- Boys?
- Let go.

34
00:01:13,187 --> 00:01:14,554
- Give me the scalpel.
- Stop!

35
00:01:14,588 --> 00:01:16,489
- Give me the scalpel, Grayson.
Give me the scalpel! - Stop it!

36
00:01:16,523 --> 00:01:18,791
Step away from the table.
I'm gonna cut her right now.

37
00:01:18,826 --> 00:01:19,859
- Step away!
- Okay, stop it!

38
00:01:19,893 --> 00:01:20,860
- Away!
- Stop it!

39
00:01:20,894 --> 00:01:22,128
Seriously, that's the last time

40
00:01:22,162 --> 00:01:24,030
I watch "Grey's" reruns
right before I go to sleep.

41
00:01:24,064 --> 00:01:25,465
It's weird, right?

42
00:01:25,499 --> 00:01:26,999
Owen and Grayson?

43
00:01:27,034 --> 00:01:29,102
The dream means you're in transition,

44
00:01:29,136 --> 00:01:31,537
like a caterpillar
before it turns into a butterfly

45
00:01:31,572 --> 00:01:33,406
or Anne Hathaway
after "The Princess Diaries"

46
00:01:33,440 --> 00:01:34,807
but before she went topless.

47
00:01:34,842 --> 00:01:35,942
Mm.

48
00:01:35,976 --> 00:01:38,378
But I'm not really
thinking of Grayson anymore.

49
00:01:38,412 --> 00:01:39,645
Mm?

50
00:01:39,680 --> 00:01:40,513
What?

51
00:01:41,348 --> 00:01:42,281
I'm not.

52
00:01:42,316 --> 00:01:44,717
Well, maybe he's thinking of you.

53
00:01:44,752 --> 00:01:46,185
What?

54
00:01:46,220 --> 00:01:48,788
Okay, so, last night, he showed up,

55
00:01:48,822 --> 00:01:51,591
and he had all these questions
about you... both of you.

56
00:01:51,625 --> 00:01:52,558
What's both of me?

57
00:01:52,593 --> 00:01:54,427
Jane and Deb.

58
00:01:54,461 --> 00:01:56,362
Mm-hmm.

59
00:01:56,397 --> 00:01:58,531
Like, did I know that Jane
got shot the same day Deb died?

60
00:01:58,565 --> 00:02:01,167
What if he's connecting the dots
a... and he knows?

61
00:02:01,201 --> 00:02:02,668
[ Scoffs ] He knows what...

62
00:02:02,703 --> 00:02:04,537
that my soul went into Jane's body?

63
00:02:04,571 --> 00:02:06,305
[ Chuckling ] No. It's impossible.

64
00:02:06,340 --> 00:02:08,307
Grayson is far too rational for that.

65
00:02:08,342 --> 00:02:10,910
Listen, sweetie, I really do
appreciate your concern,

66
00:02:10,944 --> 00:02:14,547
but I just... I know Grayson,

67
00:02:14,581 --> 00:02:17,150
and he's not connecting any dots.

68
00:02:17,184 --> 00:02:18,885
[ Chuckles ]

69
00:02:18,919 --> 00:02:20,753
Oh. I got to get to work.

70
00:02:20,788 --> 00:02:21,988
Bye.

71
00:02:22,022 --> 00:02:23,322
Bye.

72
00:02:25,592 --> 00:02:27,627
[ Elevator bell dings ]

73
00:02:27,661 --> 00:02:29,162
Roll with me, Jane.

74
00:02:29,196 --> 00:02:31,731
Okay. That is so 10 years ago.

75
00:02:31,765 --> 00:02:33,533
Or is it 10 years from now?

76
00:02:33,567 --> 00:02:34,934
No, it's what I said.

77
00:02:34,968 --> 00:02:37,136
Hey, so, listen, so, I was pondering.

78
00:02:37,171 --> 00:02:39,338
Why you're riding a Segway
through an office?

79
00:02:39,373 --> 00:02:40,807
Come on, Jane. Be serious for a second.

80
00:02:40,841 --> 00:02:42,909
I am. I'm really wondering.

81
00:02:44,878 --> 00:02:47,547
You know how your previous
guardian angel lived with you?

82
00:02:47,581 --> 00:02:49,749
- You're not living with me.
- Fred lived with you.

83
00:02:49,783 --> 00:02:51,284
Yeah, 'cause I liked Fred.

84
00:02:51,318 --> 00:02:52,452
And do you know what's terrible?

85
00:02:52,486 --> 00:02:54,220
I'm the only one who remembers him.

86
00:02:54,254 --> 00:02:56,889
Stacy was in love with him.
She doesn't even have a clue.

87
00:02:56,924 --> 00:02:58,825
Ooh. That sounds like a complaint.

88
00:02:58,859 --> 00:03:00,393
It is a complaint.

89
00:03:00,427 --> 00:03:02,462
I only take complaints
on alternate mondays.

90
00:03:02,496 --> 00:03:05,298
And... rolling.

91
00:03:05,332 --> 00:03:07,133
[ Knock on door ]

92
00:03:07,167 --> 00:03:09,001
Hey. You wanted to see me?

93
00:03:09,036 --> 00:03:10,670
Please call your father back.

94
00:03:10,704 --> 00:03:12,004
What?

95
00:03:12,039 --> 00:03:13,940
You've been ignoring his messages.

96
00:03:13,974 --> 00:03:15,608
Uh, yes, but how do you know that?

97
00:03:15,642 --> 00:03:17,210
Well, when he couldn't reach you,

98
00:03:17,244 --> 00:03:19,212
he called my office.

99
00:03:19,246 --> 00:03:20,913
[ Sighing ] Oh. I'm sorry.

100
00:03:20,948 --> 00:03:22,482
Every time he calls, he wants money.

101
00:03:22,516 --> 00:03:24,150
I haven't spoken to the guy in years.

102
00:03:24,184 --> 00:03:25,785
I don't want to drag you into this.

103
00:03:25,819 --> 00:03:26,819
His address.

104
00:03:26,854 --> 00:03:29,489
He said you didn't have it.

105
00:03:31,291 --> 00:03:32,325
Bel Air?

106
00:03:33,327 --> 00:03:36,162
He's expecting you for lunch.

107
00:03:37,097 --> 00:03:38,431
[ Explosions ]

108
00:03:38,465 --> 00:03:39,899
- Where's the ax?!
- Behind you!

109
00:03:39,933 --> 00:03:41,934
- W... where's the flamethrower?!
- Behind you! Behind you!

110
00:03:41,969 --> 00:03:43,202
[ Groans ]

111
00:03:43,237 --> 00:03:44,904
- You're too late, man.
- Ah, that's an awesome game.

112
00:03:44,938 --> 00:03:46,205
Yeah, it's coming out next Christmas.

113
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:47,874
I'll sign you up as a beta tester.

114
00:03:47,908 --> 00:03:49,876
- Who's the kid?
- Your 10:00.

115
00:03:49,910 --> 00:03:52,678
He is the C.E.O.
of a computer-game company.

116
00:03:52,713 --> 00:03:53,813
16 years old.

117
00:03:53,847 --> 00:03:55,882
But don't try to beat him
at "Combat Town."

118
00:03:55,916 --> 00:03:59,118
He dominates... probably
because he designed it.

119
00:04:00,888 --> 00:04:03,289
I'm being honored at
a software developers convention

120
00:04:03,323 --> 00:04:04,790
in Buenos Aires next month.

121
00:04:04,825 --> 00:04:06,659
Biggest one in the Southern hemisphere.

122
00:04:06,693 --> 00:04:09,061
Problem is, I can't go.

123
00:04:09,096 --> 00:04:10,530
Is it a visa issue?

124
00:04:10,564 --> 00:04:13,199
It's a dad issue. He won't let me go.

125
00:04:14,101 --> 00:04:15,902
O... okay.

126
00:04:15,936 --> 00:04:18,337
I want to sue him for
permission. I found precedent.

127
00:04:18,372 --> 00:04:20,439
Take a look at that.

128
00:04:20,474 --> 00:04:23,142
Now, in 2002, a 14-year-old sued her dad

129
00:04:23,176 --> 00:04:25,011
just so he would allow her
to go on a school field trip.

130
00:04:25,045 --> 00:04:26,946
Well, your dad must have a good reason.

131
00:04:26,980 --> 00:04:28,247
Yeah.

132
00:04:28,282 --> 00:04:30,149
Yeah, it's called being
an overprotective single parent.

133
00:04:30,183 --> 00:04:32,351
Sam, I worry that taking your dad to court

134
00:04:32,386 --> 00:04:35,254
may not get the result
that you're looking for.

135
00:04:35,289 --> 00:04:37,757
So how about, uh, a mediation?

136
00:04:37,791 --> 00:04:39,959
Sure. We could try that first.

137
00:04:39,993 --> 00:04:41,160
Okay.

138
00:04:41,194 --> 00:04:42,528
But when it doesn't work, I want to sue.

139
00:04:44,264 --> 00:04:45,631
[ Chuckles ]

140
00:04:45,666 --> 00:04:46,933
But I might just take a little bit of this.
[ Cellphone rings ]

141
00:04:46,967 --> 00:04:48,801
- It's a nice lunch item, but...
- Hello?

142
00:04:48,835 --> 00:04:50,036
Who is this?

143
00:04:50,070 --> 00:04:51,037
Who's this?

144
00:04:51,071 --> 00:04:52,138
I asked you first.

145
00:04:52,172 --> 00:04:54,273
- You called me.
[ Sighs ] - Fine.

146
00:04:54,308 --> 00:04:56,442
I will assume this is the b-i-t-c-h

147
00:04:56,476 --> 00:04:58,844
that took my phone
and replaced it with hers.

148
00:04:58,879 --> 00:05:00,513
Oh, my God!

149
00:05:00,547 --> 00:05:05,184
Then I will assume
this is the c-r-a-z...z...

150
00:05:05,218 --> 00:05:07,453
The crazy person who crank-calls me

151
00:05:07,487 --> 00:05:08,721
in the middle of the day

152
00:05:08,755 --> 00:05:10,756
to accuse me of stealing her phone,

153
00:05:10,791 --> 00:05:11,924
which I know I didn't

154
00:05:11,959 --> 00:05:14,460
because I'm talking to her on my phone...

155
00:05:14,494 --> 00:05:15,995
a special-edition...

156
00:05:16,029 --> 00:05:20,433
Both: sparkly pink,
bedazzled touch-screen.

157
00:05:20,467 --> 00:05:22,201
[ Chuckles nervously ]

158
00:05:22,235 --> 00:05:24,837
You know what?
I think I've got your phone.

159
00:05:24,871 --> 00:05:26,105
[ Chuckles nervously ]

160
00:05:26,139 --> 00:05:27,873
Can we exchange phones now?

161
00:05:27,908 --> 00:05:28,808
Totally.

162
00:05:28,842 --> 00:05:31,243
Oh, hey, how did you get this number?

163
00:05:31,278 --> 00:05:33,613
Just give me your address.

164
00:05:39,987 --> 00:05:42,788
[ Doorbell rings ]

165
00:05:45,692 --> 00:05:47,793
[ Chuckling ]
Hey! Kimmy, you made it!

166
00:05:47,828 --> 00:05:49,662
[ Chuckling nervously ]
Hey, dad.

167
00:05:49,696 --> 00:05:51,330
What are you doing here?

168
00:05:51,365 --> 00:05:53,099
Well, I was just making lunch.

169
00:05:53,133 --> 00:05:55,901
No, I mean, um... you live here?

170
00:05:55,936 --> 00:05:59,372
Uh, did I not just open the front door?

171
00:05:59,406 --> 00:06:00,406
Dad, you're a janitor.

172
00:06:00,440 --> 00:06:01,941
Did you win the lottery or something?

173
00:06:01,975 --> 00:06:04,477
Oh, no, no, no, no. I got fired.

174
00:06:04,511 --> 00:06:06,612
It's an interesting story. Come on in.

175
00:06:08,248 --> 00:06:11,684
Oh, yeah... swimming pool, tennis courts.

176
00:06:11,718 --> 00:06:15,321
Look at this...
beautiful gourmet kitchen, huh?

177
00:06:15,355 --> 00:06:16,322
It sure is.

178
00:06:16,356 --> 00:06:18,424
This sink here... 100% pure copper.

179
00:06:18,458 --> 00:06:20,426
I feel like the king of England.

180
00:06:20,460 --> 00:06:22,628
Look at this... I'm making lemonade

181
00:06:22,663 --> 00:06:24,196
from the grove out back.

182
00:06:24,231 --> 00:06:25,731
[ Chuckles nervously ]

183
00:06:25,766 --> 00:06:27,833
What was I talking about?

184
00:06:27,868 --> 00:06:30,069
EVK Insurance fired you?

185
00:06:30,103 --> 00:06:32,071
Oh, yeah, yeah, after 14 years of service.

186
00:06:32,105 --> 00:06:33,239
Imagine that.

187
00:06:33,273 --> 00:06:34,807
I figured, eh, no big deal.

188
00:06:34,841 --> 00:06:36,575
I got a retirement fund, right?

189
00:06:36,610 --> 00:06:37,710
Well, wrong.

190
00:06:37,744 --> 00:06:40,546
It turns out EVK under-funded
my retirement account,

191
00:06:40,580 --> 00:06:42,481
so I called a lawyer.

192
00:06:42,516 --> 00:06:44,517
The guy gets me a $34,000 judgment, right?

193
00:06:44,551 --> 00:06:45,751
Pretty good?

194
00:06:45,786 --> 00:06:46,752
Wrong!

195
00:06:46,787 --> 00:06:48,654
It turns out EVK declares bankruptcy.

196
00:06:48,689 --> 00:06:51,323
So now they don't have to pay you.

197
00:06:51,358 --> 00:06:55,061
That's right, even though
Elliot Rollins, their C.E.O.,

198
00:06:55,095 --> 00:06:58,431
gets a bonus of $2.6 million.

199
00:06:58,465 --> 00:06:59,899
Dad?

200
00:06:59,933 --> 00:07:00,933
Yeah, pickles?

201
00:07:00,967 --> 00:07:02,435
Whose house is this?

202
00:07:02,469 --> 00:07:03,869
[ Chuckles ]
Elliot Rollins'.

203
00:07:03,904 --> 00:07:05,971
He owns six or seven of 'em.

204
00:07:06,006 --> 00:07:09,008
You're trespassing. We shouldn't
even be here right now.

205
00:07:09,042 --> 00:07:11,811
Wrong. I'm collecting the $34k
he owes me in back rent.

206
00:07:11,845 --> 00:07:13,145
Oh, my God.

207
00:07:13,180 --> 00:07:14,613
Oh, sweetheart, h... he had a party here

208
00:07:14,648 --> 00:07:16,215
a couple of months ago for the company,

209
00:07:16,249 --> 00:07:18,651
and I was asked to help
clean up, which I did,

210
00:07:18,685 --> 00:07:20,619
and when everybody left, I stayed.

211
00:07:20,654 --> 00:07:22,788
Does Rollins know you're here?

212
00:07:22,823 --> 00:07:25,024
Oh, yeah... one of the neighbors
blew the whistle,

213
00:07:25,058 --> 00:07:27,126
so Rollins shows up this morning,

214
00:07:27,160 --> 00:07:29,295
starts screaming
if I'm not out of here by noon,

215
00:07:29,329 --> 00:07:30,329
he's gonna call the cops.

216
00:07:30,363 --> 00:07:32,431
Dad, this is crazy, even for you.

217
00:07:32,466 --> 00:07:35,367
What? The place rents for $11,000 a month.

218
00:07:35,402 --> 00:07:37,503
I got five weeks to go.

219
00:07:37,537 --> 00:07:38,971
Come on.

220
00:07:39,005 --> 00:07:40,439
You're having lemonade, right?

221
00:07:41,341 --> 00:07:42,274
[ Sighs ]

222
00:07:42,309 --> 00:07:44,143
I reviewed Sam's legal precedent.

223
00:07:44,177 --> 00:07:46,512
It's Canadian
and was overturned on appeal.

224
00:07:46,546 --> 00:07:48,814
If we're going to court,
we need something else.

225
00:07:48,849 --> 00:07:51,317
I'm still hoping
we settle this over coffee

226
00:07:51,351 --> 00:07:53,519
in his dad's living room.

227
00:07:53,553 --> 00:07:54,687
[ Sighs ]

228
00:07:56,089 --> 00:07:58,457
Was there something else?

229
00:08:01,995 --> 00:08:05,564
Do you... realize you were shot
the same day Deb died?

230
00:08:06,433 --> 00:08:07,600
Oh.

231
00:08:07,634 --> 00:08:09,568
Well, I'm sure lots of people
were shot that day.

232
00:08:09,603 --> 00:08:12,505
At exactly 10:14 in the morning?

233
00:08:12,539 --> 00:08:14,039
Hey. Hope I'm not interrupting.

234
00:08:14,074 --> 00:08:15,574
Actually, I don't care, because...

235
00:08:15,609 --> 00:08:16,542
You've got big news.

236
00:08:16,576 --> 00:08:17,810
How do you know that?

237
00:08:17,844 --> 00:08:19,545
Because you bought a new suit,
which means...

238
00:08:19,579 --> 00:08:22,715
I'm back on the bench. Just
talked with the presiding judge.

239
00:08:22,749 --> 00:08:24,383
I am reclaiming my old courtroom.

240
00:08:24,417 --> 00:08:26,252
That's fantastic. Isn't that fantastic?

241
00:08:26,286 --> 00:08:27,920
That's fantastic.

242
00:08:27,954 --> 00:08:29,388
Maybe you should get a new suit, Grayson,

243
00:08:29,422 --> 00:08:31,123
seeing as I'll be judging you
again real soon.

244
00:08:31,158 --> 00:08:32,758
Not that I've ever stopped.

245
00:08:32,793 --> 00:08:34,727
- I'm kidding.
- That's funny.

246
00:08:34,761 --> 00:08:36,529
Honestly, I want an honest
opinion. What do you think?

247
00:08:36,563 --> 00:08:37,630
Uh...

248
00:08:37,664 --> 00:08:40,032
Tell me the truth.
Are the sleeves too long?

249
00:08:40,066 --> 00:08:41,600
They are perfect. Don't change a thing.

250
00:08:41,635 --> 00:08:43,202
- You think so?
- No, no, they're perfect.

251
00:08:43,236 --> 00:08:44,770
- You know what we could do?
- What?

252
00:08:44,805 --> 00:08:46,539
We could salsa.
[ Laughs ]

253
00:08:46,573 --> 00:08:49,308
- Who's leading?
- You are! You're always leading!

254
00:08:52,644 --> 00:08:54,512
Yeah, well, I don't understand

255
00:08:54,546 --> 00:08:57,115
why you hired lawyers
to talk to your father!

256
00:08:57,149 --> 00:08:58,149
'Cause you won't listen to me!

257
00:08:58,183 --> 00:09:00,385
Okay, this trip is really important.

258
00:09:00,419 --> 00:09:01,486
I am listening, Sam,

259
00:09:01,520 --> 00:09:04,122
and I said no... end of story.

260
00:09:04,156 --> 00:09:07,258
Dad, you said you'd take me to Lindsey's.

261
00:09:07,292 --> 00:09:09,360
Uh... okay, finish your homework,

262
00:09:09,395 --> 00:09:10,395
and then we'll go.

263
00:09:10,429 --> 00:09:12,163
Listen, I don't know what he's told you,

264
00:09:12,197 --> 00:09:13,531
but nobody's prouder of Sam.

265
00:09:13,565 --> 00:09:16,167
Still, he's not going
to South America by himself.

266
00:09:16,201 --> 00:09:17,702
He's only 16.

267
00:09:17,736 --> 00:09:18,970
Why not go with him?

268
00:09:19,905 --> 00:09:21,372
I'm an L.A.P.D. detective.

269
00:09:21,407 --> 00:09:23,674
I got two kids, a full-time job,

270
00:09:23,709 --> 00:09:26,043
and since my wife died, it's just me.

271
00:09:26,078 --> 00:09:28,246
Now, if you'll excuse me.

272
00:09:28,280 --> 00:09:30,615
Show your friends out.

273
00:09:32,184 --> 00:09:34,118
I want to go to court.

274
00:09:34,153 --> 00:09:35,219
We looked into it.

275
00:09:35,254 --> 00:09:37,121
Your lawsuit would get tossed
in 30 seconds.

276
00:09:37,156 --> 00:09:38,956
As long as you're a minor,
your father has the right

277
00:09:38,991 --> 00:09:40,391
to prevent you from traveling overseas.

278
00:09:40,426 --> 00:09:42,160
Well, then we'll sue for emancipation.

279
00:09:42,194 --> 00:09:44,061
Eman... no.

280
00:09:44,096 --> 00:09:46,330
Emancipation is drastic.

281
00:09:46,365 --> 00:09:47,632
It tells your father

282
00:09:47,666 --> 00:09:49,367
that you don't want him in your life.

283
00:09:49,401 --> 00:09:51,369
- How do we do it?
- We don't.

284
00:09:51,403 --> 00:09:53,171
The court needs to see you have
an independent source of income,

285
00:09:53,205 --> 00:09:55,306
you can live on your own, and
that it's in your best interests.

286
00:09:55,340 --> 00:09:56,574
Okay, before you do this,

287
00:09:56,608 --> 00:09:59,110
let's... let's just breathe,
and we'll discuss.

288
00:09:59,144 --> 00:10:01,145
Hold on. You're my lawyer.
You're not my mother.

289
00:10:01,180 --> 00:10:02,647
I... I want to be emancipated.

290
00:10:06,585 --> 00:10:08,052
That's the son of a bitch right there.

291
00:10:08,086 --> 00:10:10,154
Let us take care of this, sir.

292
00:10:10,189 --> 00:10:12,089
Hey. Uh, I'm, uh, renting the place.

293
00:10:12,124 --> 00:10:13,825
Rollins: - It's not for rent.
- Officer, if I may.

294
00:10:13,859 --> 00:10:14,759
Who are you?

295
00:10:14,793 --> 00:10:16,360
I'm Kim Kaswell. I'm his lawyer.

296
00:10:17,396 --> 00:10:18,496
I need to see his I.D., please.

297
00:10:18,530 --> 00:10:21,299
Oh, yes, sir. Here's my license.
Note the address.

298
00:10:21,333 --> 00:10:22,900
1452 St. Cloud Drive.

299
00:10:22,935 --> 00:10:24,936
Are you kidding? That's
this address. It's my house.

300
00:10:24,970 --> 00:10:26,304
You changed your address?

301
00:10:26,338 --> 00:10:28,840
- This lowlife is a trespasser.
Larry: - Lowlife?

302
00:10:28,874 --> 00:10:31,242
I scrubbed your floors for 14 years.
You don't even know my name.

303
00:10:31,276 --> 00:10:32,477
"Lowlife." Ha!

304
00:10:32,511 --> 00:10:34,612
You've got handcuffs. Use them.

305
00:10:34,646 --> 00:10:36,781
Officer, my client is a presumptive tenant

306
00:10:36,815 --> 00:10:39,817
until a judge says otherwise,
and he has rights.

307
00:10:39,852 --> 00:10:41,853
Rights? He has the right
to get his ass tasered.

308
00:10:41,887 --> 00:10:44,355
You listen to me, krupke...
my taxes pay your salary.

309
00:10:44,389 --> 00:10:47,191
I'm ordering you to get
this jackass out of my house.

310
00:10:47,226 --> 00:10:48,860
Step back, Mr. Rollins.

311
00:10:48,894 --> 00:10:49,760
Excuse me?

312
00:10:49,795 --> 00:10:50,962
Her taxes pay my salary, too.

313
00:10:50,996 --> 00:10:52,930
For now, he's, uh, what did you call it?

314
00:10:52,965 --> 00:10:54,031
Presumptive tenant.

315
00:10:54,066 --> 00:10:55,299
Return to your vehicle.

316
00:10:58,637 --> 00:11:00,238
[ Police radio chatter ]

317
00:11:01,640 --> 00:11:03,674
You want to go see the wine cellar?

318
00:11:03,709 --> 00:11:05,543
It's a doozy.

319
00:11:05,577 --> 00:11:06,811
[ Sighs ]

320
00:11:06,845 --> 00:11:08,346
[ Knock on door ]

321
00:11:08,380 --> 00:11:09,680
Hey, Nikki.
[ Bell dings ]

322
00:11:09,715 --> 00:11:11,582
Oh. That's the oven. Come on in.

323
00:11:13,285 --> 00:11:14,785
[ Door closes ]

324
00:11:14,820 --> 00:11:16,087
Nice place.

325
00:11:16,121 --> 00:11:17,021
Thank you!

326
00:11:17,055 --> 00:11:19,156
[ Sighing ]
Oh.

327
00:11:19,191 --> 00:11:20,358
Hmm.

328
00:11:20,392 --> 00:11:22,260
What the hell is that?

329
00:11:22,294 --> 00:11:25,029
It was supposed to be a cake.

330
00:11:25,063 --> 00:11:26,297
So you're, like, a baker?

331
00:11:26,331 --> 00:11:28,032
Not really.
[ Chuckles ]

332
00:11:28,066 --> 00:11:29,600
This morning, I felt a bit down,

333
00:11:29,635 --> 00:11:31,469
like something was missing from my life,

334
00:11:31,503 --> 00:11:33,504
and I thought
it might be carbs, so I baked.

335
00:11:33,539 --> 00:11:35,673
So, why does your cake have a crust?

336
00:11:35,707 --> 00:11:37,542
I don't understand what happened.

337
00:11:37,576 --> 00:11:39,310
I mean, I followed the recipe.

338
00:11:39,344 --> 00:11:41,412
Well, the pages are stuck together.

339
00:11:41,446 --> 00:11:45,049
You combined a bundt cake with pecan pie.

340
00:11:45,083 --> 00:11:46,851
[ Chuckles ]
Sounds like me.

341
00:11:46,885 --> 00:11:49,220
I mean, it looks weird,
but it smells pretty good.

342
00:11:49,254 --> 00:11:51,022
[ Sniffs ]
It does.

343
00:11:51,056 --> 00:11:52,189
Let me try.

344
00:11:52,224 --> 00:11:54,025
[ Blows ]

345
00:11:55,227 --> 00:11:57,128
Oh, my God! It's delicious!

346
00:11:57,162 --> 00:11:58,429
You just invented a new dessert.

347
00:11:58,463 --> 00:11:59,864
I'm an inventor.

348
00:11:59,898 --> 00:12:01,666
You need to name this.

349
00:12:01,700 --> 00:12:03,301
Umm... cake pie.

350
00:12:03,335 --> 00:12:05,102
Mnh-mnh. Pie cake?

351
00:12:05,137 --> 00:12:06,704
[ Gasps ]
I've got it.

352
00:12:06,738 --> 00:12:08,205
It's a pake!

353
00:12:08,907 --> 00:12:09,740
[ Knock on door ]

354
00:12:09,775 --> 00:12:10,775
Hey.

355
00:12:10,809 --> 00:12:13,177
Hey. I'm almost through the financials.

356
00:12:13,211 --> 00:12:15,146
This kid makes 10 times what I do.

357
00:12:15,180 --> 00:12:17,114
It doesn't mean he should be emancipated.

358
00:12:17,149 --> 00:12:19,083
He's the client.

359
00:12:19,117 --> 00:12:21,485
Which is why I drafted
a mitigation statement.

360
00:12:21,520 --> 00:12:22,920
Would you take a look at it?

361
00:12:23,922 --> 00:12:25,923
"Mapping your past lives"?

362
00:12:25,958 --> 00:12:27,892
Just a little research.

363
00:12:27,926 --> 00:12:30,227
On reincarnation? You?

364
00:12:31,563 --> 00:12:32,597
I don't know.

365
00:12:32,631 --> 00:12:35,700
I find the whole idea of it,
uh, reassuring.

366
00:12:35,734 --> 00:12:37,368
What about you?

367
00:12:37,402 --> 00:12:41,205
Do you think a person
can come back as someone else?

368
00:12:41,239 --> 00:12:42,907
Oh, my God, guys.

369
00:12:42,941 --> 00:12:44,575
[ Sighs ]
You've got to see this.

370
00:12:44,610 --> 00:12:45,643
Okay.

371
00:12:45,677 --> 00:12:46,844
[ Keyboard clacks ]

372
00:12:46,878 --> 00:12:49,947
The county has no record
of Sam's birth certificate,

373
00:12:49,982 --> 00:12:51,716
and his social security number is a fake.

374
00:12:51,750 --> 00:12:52,683
Weird.

375
00:12:52,718 --> 00:12:54,085
Well, 10 years of watching "Dateline"

376
00:12:54,119 --> 00:12:55,586
has made me pretty suspicious,

377
00:12:55,621 --> 00:12:57,688
so I scoured all
the missing-persons databases,

378
00:12:57,723 --> 00:12:59,256
and this is what came up.

379
00:13:00,325 --> 00:13:01,792
I don't understand. That's a baby.

380
00:13:01,827 --> 00:13:04,428
His name is Adam Gates.
He was kidnapped 15 years ago.

381
00:13:04,463 --> 00:13:06,464
This is what he would look like today.

382
00:13:06,498 --> 00:13:07,999
[ Gasps ]

383
00:13:08,033 --> 00:13:09,967
[ Siren wails ]

384
00:13:11,703 --> 00:13:13,237
[ Knock on door ]

385
00:13:16,208 --> 00:13:17,174
What the hell is this?

386
00:13:17,209 --> 00:13:18,709
We've got a warrant. Step back.

387
00:13:18,744 --> 00:13:20,411
- My kids are in here!
- Mr. Forman, you're under arrest.

388
00:13:20,445 --> 00:13:22,046
- What are the charges?
- Kidnapping.

389
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:23,614
- W... what's going on right now?
- Dad?

390
00:13:23,649 --> 00:13:25,650
You and your sister are going
with child protective services.

391
00:13:25,684 --> 00:13:27,218
Officer: You have
the right to remain silent.

392
00:13:27,252 --> 00:13:28,986
Lily: Sam! Daddy, no!

393
00:13:29,021 --> 00:13:30,087
Anything you say can and will be
used against you in a court of law.

394
00:13:30,122 --> 00:13:31,989
- Dad!
- It's gonna be okay, sweetie.

395
00:13:32,024 --> 00:13:33,457
Jane, what did you do?!

396
00:13:42,223 --> 00:13:43,389
[ Door closes ]

397
00:13:43,424 --> 00:13:45,091
Heard you wanted to see me.

398
00:13:45,126 --> 00:13:47,627
I need for you to hear the whole story.

399
00:13:47,661 --> 00:13:49,129
You kidnapped a child.

400
00:13:49,163 --> 00:13:50,897
You thought the law didn't apply to you

401
00:13:50,931 --> 00:13:52,699
because you're a cop, but you're wrong.

402
00:13:52,733 --> 00:13:54,000
Please.

403
00:13:54,034 --> 00:13:56,002
Sit down.

404
00:13:56,036 --> 00:13:57,737
Please.

405
00:13:59,807 --> 00:14:01,574
Okay.

406
00:14:03,944 --> 00:14:05,378
What?

407
00:14:05,412 --> 00:14:06,446
[ Sighs ]

408
00:14:06,480 --> 00:14:08,181
New year's eve, 15 years ago.

409
00:14:08,215 --> 00:14:09,215
I caught this case.

410
00:14:09,250 --> 00:14:10,283
Mm-hmm.

411
00:14:10,317 --> 00:14:12,285
A meth dealer was killed
in a condemned house.

412
00:14:12,319 --> 00:14:13,419
Right.

413
00:14:13,454 --> 00:14:17,223
No electricity, rotted food,
drug paraphernalia.

414
00:14:17,258 --> 00:14:19,993
In the garage, I found a 1-year-old boy

415
00:14:20,027 --> 00:14:22,061
covered in battery grease.

416
00:14:22,096 --> 00:14:23,129
Adam Gates?

417
00:14:23,164 --> 00:14:24,464
Yeah.

418
00:14:24,498 --> 00:14:26,699
I called protective services.

419
00:14:26,734 --> 00:14:28,334
No one came.

420
00:14:28,369 --> 00:14:30,870
So... I took him home.

421
00:14:30,905 --> 00:14:34,207
My wife and I cleaned him up, fed him,

422
00:14:34,241 --> 00:14:36,342
and waited for someone to get in touch.

423
00:14:36,377 --> 00:14:37,377
Mm-hmm.

424
00:14:37,411 --> 00:14:38,578
But no one did.

425
00:14:38,612 --> 00:14:41,014
This... this kid

426
00:14:41,048 --> 00:14:43,483
had fallen completely through the cracks.

427
00:14:43,517 --> 00:14:45,051
What about his family?

428
00:14:45,085 --> 00:14:46,252
His father was dead.

429
00:14:46,287 --> 00:14:49,822
His mother was a hard-core
drug user in and out of jail.

430
00:14:49,857 --> 00:14:52,258
I mean, she brought that kid

431
00:14:52,293 --> 00:14:54,694
to this dealer's house and forgot him.

432
00:14:54,728 --> 00:14:58,898
So Sarah and I decided
to raise him as our own.

433
00:15:03,270 --> 00:15:06,239
I always knew this day could come.

434
00:15:06,273 --> 00:15:08,741
But I had to take the risk.

435
00:15:08,776 --> 00:15:11,544
That's why you didn't
want Sam to travel...

436
00:15:11,579 --> 00:15:16,382
because the passport application
would've given him away.

437
00:15:18,552 --> 00:15:20,220
They won't let me see him.

438
00:15:20,254 --> 00:15:22,455
Please.

439
00:15:22,489 --> 00:15:24,991
Just...

440
00:15:25,025 --> 00:15:26,759
tell him I'm sorry.

441
00:15:28,229 --> 00:15:30,363
Tell him I love him.

442
00:15:35,402 --> 00:15:37,003
- Oh, my God.
- Which one is that?

443
00:15:37,037 --> 00:15:39,572
Boston cream pake... best one yet.

444
00:15:41,942 --> 00:15:43,109
[ Muffled ] - Wow.
- Mm-hmm.

445
00:15:43,143 --> 00:15:45,278
You know what this needs?

446
00:15:45,312 --> 00:15:46,479
- Sprinkles!
- Sprinkles!

447
00:15:46,513 --> 00:15:48,481
I had no idea baking was this therapeutic.

448
00:15:48,515 --> 00:15:50,783
Mm. It's like yoga, but with frosting.

449
00:15:52,052 --> 00:15:53,086
- You know what?
- Hmm?

450
00:15:53,120 --> 00:15:54,721
We should go into business together.

451
00:15:54,755 --> 00:15:57,557
We can open up an awesome bakery.

452
00:15:57,591 --> 00:15:59,359
Or an awesome pakery.

453
00:15:59,393 --> 00:16:00,326
[ Both laugh ]

454
00:16:00,361 --> 00:16:01,261
One little problem...

455
00:16:01,295 --> 00:16:03,162
I don't know how to run a business.

456
00:16:03,197 --> 00:16:05,231
I have tons of experience.

457
00:16:05,266 --> 00:16:07,033
I mean, all we need is investors.

458
00:16:07,067 --> 00:16:09,035
Oh, I... I...
[ Chuckles ]

459
00:16:09,069 --> 00:16:11,004
Well, I can ask my best friend, Jane.

460
00:16:11,038 --> 00:16:13,840
She will buy a first-class
ticket on the pake train.

461
00:16:13,874 --> 00:16:14,741
[ Chuckles ]

462
00:16:14,775 --> 00:16:16,576
- To us.
- To us.

463
00:16:16,610 --> 00:16:18,611
It's a lot to process.

464
00:16:18,646 --> 00:16:20,413
You doing all right?

465
00:16:20,447 --> 00:16:21,347
Yeah.

466
00:16:21,382 --> 00:16:23,750
What happens now?

467
00:16:23,784 --> 00:16:28,788
DCS will place you and Lily
with a family during the trial

468
00:16:28,822 --> 00:16:30,823
and then somewhere more permanent.

469
00:16:30,858 --> 00:16:33,660
And your father
will most likely go to jail.

470
00:16:33,694 --> 00:16:34,661
No.

471
00:16:34,695 --> 00:16:36,195
Jane, this isn't... this isn't fair.

472
00:16:36,230 --> 00:16:38,031
I'm gonna be on my own
in a year or two anyway,

473
00:16:38,065 --> 00:16:40,466
but Lily's only 9 years old.

474
00:16:40,501 --> 00:16:42,802
She's gonna grow up
with strangers. Oh, my God.

475
00:16:42,836 --> 00:16:44,804
If I hadn't filed for
emancipation, this would've...

476
00:16:44,838 --> 00:16:46,105
Sam, this is not your fault.

477
00:16:46,140 --> 00:16:47,407
[ Sighs ]

478
00:16:47,441 --> 00:16:49,676
Your father made a decision
years ago. You were just a baby.

479
00:16:49,710 --> 00:16:50,877
Will you represent him?

480
00:16:50,911 --> 00:16:52,478
Sam, I am your lawyer.

481
00:16:52,513 --> 00:16:53,846
He's my father.

482
00:16:53,881 --> 00:16:56,849
He's the only one I've ever known.

483
00:16:58,352 --> 00:16:59,452
Please.

484
00:17:03,524 --> 00:17:08,127
All rise for the honorable
judge Owen French!

485
00:17:08,162 --> 00:17:10,530
I know him. He's a fair judge.

486
00:17:10,564 --> 00:17:13,099
Who's here for the Greenstine Bar Mitzvah?

487
00:17:13,133 --> 00:17:14,767
[ Laughter ]
I kid. Sit.

488
00:17:16,970 --> 00:17:19,672
Three lawyers for an unlawful detainer?

489
00:17:19,707 --> 00:17:20,807
Very David vs. Goliath.

490
00:17:20,841 --> 00:17:22,642
This is going to be truly biblical.

491
00:17:22,676 --> 00:17:24,277
Your Honor, this hearing is ridiculous.

492
00:17:24,311 --> 00:17:25,845
We move for an immediate eviction order.

493
00:17:25,879 --> 00:17:27,280
Last I heard, Your Honor,

494
00:17:27,314 --> 00:17:28,715
you're the one
who decides what's ridiculous.

495
00:17:28,749 --> 00:17:30,917
Miss Kaswell speaks the truth.

496
00:17:30,951 --> 00:17:32,752
I am the arbiter of ridiculous.

497
00:17:32,786 --> 00:17:34,420
Mr. Kaswell, come on down.

498
00:17:34,455 --> 00:17:36,556
You claim to be a tenant,
yet you had no lease.

499
00:17:36,590 --> 00:17:40,226
Well, it... it was a non-written lease.

500
00:17:40,260 --> 00:17:41,260
A non-written lease?

501
00:17:41,295 --> 00:17:42,595
Per California property code,

502
00:17:42,629 --> 00:17:43,863
a verbal lease is binding

503
00:17:43,897 --> 00:17:46,265
if the term is not greater than a year.

504
00:17:46,300 --> 00:17:48,434
There's no lease, verbal or otherwise.

505
00:17:48,469 --> 00:17:49,836
What did Mr. Rollins say to you

506
00:17:49,870 --> 00:17:51,604
on the night of the party at his house?

507
00:17:51,638 --> 00:17:54,540
Well, he, uh, said, "look,
stay as long as you want."

508
00:17:54,575 --> 00:17:56,075
- Oh, come on.
- Those were his words.

509
00:17:56,110 --> 00:17:57,443
I see no receipt for payment.

510
00:17:57,478 --> 00:18:01,080
We assert Mr. Kaswell
pre-paid Mr. Rollins his rent

511
00:18:01,115 --> 00:18:03,049
in the form of a $34,000 judgment

512
00:18:03,083 --> 00:18:04,817
that Mr. Rollins' company owes him.

513
00:18:04,852 --> 00:18:06,753
Come on! The man's a trespasser!

514
00:18:06,787 --> 00:18:08,221
Simmer down.

515
00:18:08,255 --> 00:18:10,423
Ms. Kaswell, while I find
EVK's actions contemptible,

516
00:18:10,457 --> 00:18:12,458
I can't justify
calling Mr. Kaswell a tenant.

517
00:18:12,493 --> 00:18:14,327
One minute, Your Honor.

518
00:18:14,361 --> 00:18:16,529
We would like to amend
Mr. Kaswell's motion.

519
00:18:16,563 --> 00:18:17,663
We would?

520
00:18:17,698 --> 00:18:19,999
Larry Kaswell is not a tenant.

521
00:18:20,033 --> 00:18:21,768
I'm not?

522
00:18:21,802 --> 00:18:23,569
He is, however, a lienholder

523
00:18:23,604 --> 00:18:25,938
against EVK Insurance Corporation

524
00:18:25,973 --> 00:18:29,208
and, as such, is entitled
to temporary possession

525
00:18:29,243 --> 00:18:30,910
of EVK's collateral...

526
00:18:30,944 --> 00:18:33,346
namely Elliot Rollins' Bel Air home.

527
00:18:33,380 --> 00:18:36,215
Larry Kaswell's judgment
is against EVK Insurance,

528
00:18:36,250 --> 00:18:37,250
not its C.E.O.

529
00:18:37,284 --> 00:18:39,185
- One and the same.
- Exactly.

530
00:18:39,219 --> 00:18:41,988
Elliot Rollins is not only
the face of EVK Insurance,

531
00:18:42,022 --> 00:18:43,222
he is EVK Insurance.

532
00:18:43,257 --> 00:18:44,791
And if you grant us 24 hours

533
00:18:44,825 --> 00:18:47,560
and the authority to depose
the EVK board of directors,

534
00:18:47,594 --> 00:18:48,528
we'll prove it.

535
00:18:48,562 --> 00:18:49,762
Oh, give me a break!

536
00:18:49,797 --> 00:18:51,264
[ Whispering ]

537
00:18:52,166 --> 00:18:54,033
We are happy to agree.

538
00:18:54,067 --> 00:18:56,235
We'll demand attorney's fees and sanctions

539
00:18:56,270 --> 00:18:58,938
when you decide
that their case has no merit.

540
00:18:58,972 --> 00:19:01,007
So noted.

541
00:19:01,041 --> 00:19:04,777
Look at you... Han Solo
flying in to save the day.

542
00:19:04,812 --> 00:19:06,479
Oh, you finally saw that movie?

543
00:19:06,513 --> 00:19:07,480
[ Laughs ]

544
00:19:07,514 --> 00:19:09,549
Hey, thanks for your help.

545
00:19:09,583 --> 00:19:11,484
Why didn't you just tell me
what you were doing?

546
00:19:11,518 --> 00:19:13,719
Because I know
you have better things to do

547
00:19:13,754 --> 00:19:16,322
than help some crackpot
antagonize a Fortune 500 C.E.O.

548
00:19:16,356 --> 00:19:17,824
That crackpot is your father.

549
00:19:17,858 --> 00:19:19,091
Yeah.
[ Laughs ]

550
00:19:19,126 --> 00:19:21,928
Well, except for the occasional
birthday card growing up,

551
00:19:21,962 --> 00:19:23,863
I hardly ever heard from the guy.

552
00:19:23,897 --> 00:19:26,032
Now he only calls when he's in trouble.

553
00:19:26,066 --> 00:19:27,166
Phones go both ways.

554
00:19:27,201 --> 00:19:30,002
Since when do you have
a soft spot for family?

555
00:19:32,039 --> 00:19:33,439
[ Clears throat ]

556
00:19:33,474 --> 00:19:34,373
I'm sorry.

557
00:19:34,408 --> 00:19:37,477
Parker, what happened in Chicago?

558
00:19:37,511 --> 00:19:38,978
- This isn't about me.
- Like hell it isn't.

559
00:19:39,012 --> 00:19:41,214
You drop everything
to go search for your son.

560
00:19:41,248 --> 00:19:43,082
You haven't said a word about it
since you got back.

561
00:19:43,116 --> 00:19:45,551
[ Scoffs ]

562
00:19:45,586 --> 00:19:48,087
Because I never found him.

563
00:19:50,958 --> 00:19:52,258
But you looked.

564
00:19:52,292 --> 00:19:54,227
And when you see your son again,

565
00:19:54,261 --> 00:19:56,629
you'll be able to tell him that.

566
00:20:03,203 --> 00:20:04,570
You're home!

567
00:20:04,605 --> 00:20:05,605
I am.

568
00:20:05,639 --> 00:20:07,773
And you're... baking...

569
00:20:07,808 --> 00:20:09,342
with a new friend, or...

570
00:20:09,376 --> 00:20:11,711
Uh, Jane, this is Nikki. Nikki... Jane.

571
00:20:11,745 --> 00:20:12,678
Nice to meet you.

572
00:20:12,713 --> 00:20:15,214
Hi. Is that my apron?

573
00:20:15,249 --> 00:20:16,382
I need you to taste something.

574
00:20:16,416 --> 00:20:17,950
Okay. What is it?

575
00:20:17,985 --> 00:20:18,951
Our future.

576
00:20:18,986 --> 00:20:20,753
Ooh.

577
00:20:23,423 --> 00:20:24,557
[ Muffled ] Hmm.

578
00:20:24,591 --> 00:20:26,993
It's kind of like a pie but...

579
00:20:27,027 --> 00:20:27,960
kind of a...

580
00:20:27,995 --> 00:20:28,928
Cake!

581
00:20:28,962 --> 00:20:30,530
It's a pake!

582
00:20:30,564 --> 00:20:31,631
We invented it today.

583
00:20:31,665 --> 00:20:33,566
So, you'll invest, right?

584
00:20:33,600 --> 00:20:36,969
Invest... in what? A bake sale?

585
00:20:37,004 --> 00:20:38,004
No, no, no. Think bigger.

586
00:20:38,038 --> 00:20:40,306
We are going to open our own pakery.

587
00:20:40,340 --> 00:20:42,308
So, how much are you guys looking for?

588
00:20:42,342 --> 00:20:43,576
$10,000.

589
00:20:43,610 --> 00:20:44,810
Wow.

590
00:20:44,845 --> 00:20:46,045
Well, as Nikki always says,

591
00:20:46,079 --> 00:20:47,580
"it takes money to bake money."

592
00:20:47,614 --> 00:20:48,481
You say that?

593
00:20:48,515 --> 00:20:49,715
I do.

594
00:20:49,750 --> 00:20:52,418
I'm kind of surprised you're not
being more supportive.

595
00:20:52,452 --> 00:20:53,753
Oh, are you saying no?

596
00:20:53,787 --> 00:20:54,654
No!

597
00:20:54,688 --> 00:20:56,522
No, I'm not... I'm not saying no.

598
00:20:56,557 --> 00:20:59,492
I'd actually like to see
your business plan.

599
00:20:59,526 --> 00:21:01,360
I'm sorry... my what?

600
00:21:01,395 --> 00:21:03,462
Stacy, if you're gonna
ask people for money,

601
00:21:03,497 --> 00:21:05,298
don't you think you should have a plan?

602
00:21:05,332 --> 00:21:06,766
Way to rain on the parade.

603
00:21:06,800 --> 00:21:09,335
Wow. Okay, no, I'm not...
I'm not raining on anything.

604
00:21:09,369 --> 00:21:10,570
Actually, I'm...

605
00:21:10,604 --> 00:21:12,772
All day, Stacy's been saying,
"Jane will love this."

606
00:21:12,806 --> 00:21:15,308
No, I do love this. I do love this.

607
00:21:15,342 --> 00:21:16,943
Why does she need to show you
a business plan?

608
00:21:16,977 --> 00:21:18,644
She's not asking anyone for money.

609
00:21:18,679 --> 00:21:20,079
She's asking her best friend.

610
00:21:20,113 --> 00:21:22,281
Y... you know it's okay not to express

611
00:21:22,316 --> 00:21:24,517
every single thought that you have?

612
00:21:24,551 --> 00:21:26,319
I always support you, Jane,

613
00:21:26,353 --> 00:21:29,655
and I have never once asked
to see your business plan.

614
00:21:29,690 --> 00:21:30,990
I've known you less than a day,

615
00:21:31,024 --> 00:21:32,959
and I wouldn't ask
to see your business plan.

616
00:21:32,993 --> 00:21:34,260
I believe in her.

617
00:21:34,294 --> 00:21:35,494
Really, this is none of your business.

618
00:21:35,529 --> 00:21:37,697
Really, this is my business.

619
00:21:37,731 --> 00:21:39,298
It's our business.

620
00:21:39,333 --> 00:21:42,168
I'll call you later.
I don't like her energy.

621
00:21:44,404 --> 00:21:46,138
[ Door opens, closes ]

622
00:21:46,173 --> 00:21:48,207
[ Scoffs ]
Can we talk about this?

623
00:21:48,241 --> 00:21:50,443
I don't think so.

624
00:21:54,688 --> 00:21:55,988
Let me get this straight.

625
00:21:56,014 --> 00:21:58,215
You turned Bruce in,
and now you're defending him?

626
00:21:58,250 --> 00:21:59,317
That's right.

627
00:21:59,351 --> 00:22:01,419
We... we're hoping you could give us
some background

628
00:22:01,453 --> 00:22:02,954
and help us with his defense.

629
00:22:02,988 --> 00:22:04,722
Okay.

630
00:22:04,756 --> 00:22:06,390
You were with Bruce at the homicide,

631
00:22:06,425 --> 00:22:08,125
new year's eve 15 years ago, correct?

632
00:22:08,160 --> 00:22:09,660
Yeah.

633
00:22:09,695 --> 00:22:12,263
Do you remember
finding a baby at the scene?

634
00:22:12,297 --> 00:22:14,098
It was a long time ago.

635
00:22:14,132 --> 00:22:15,900
Officer, you said you were there.

636
00:22:15,934 --> 00:22:17,868
Did you see Bruce Forman
take the baby home?

637
00:22:17,903 --> 00:22:19,770
I'm not saying I saw anything,

638
00:22:19,805 --> 00:22:22,673
but if he did,
Forman gave that kid a chance.

639
00:22:22,708 --> 00:22:24,041
That's all I'm gonna say.

640
00:22:25,077 --> 00:22:27,812
- Thanks for your time.
- Thank you.

641
00:22:32,551 --> 00:22:33,851
I don't like this case.

642
00:22:33,885 --> 00:22:35,953
He lied to that kid for 15 years.

643
00:22:35,988 --> 00:22:38,689
You know what? There are
different kinds of lies.

644
00:22:38,724 --> 00:22:41,692
There are good lies and... bad lies.

645
00:22:41,727 --> 00:22:43,194
- Huh.
- What?

646
00:22:43,228 --> 00:22:45,162
Deb used to say something like that.

647
00:22:45,197 --> 00:22:47,031
She'd say there were white lies and...

648
00:22:47,065 --> 00:22:48,566
Off-white lies.
[ Laughs ]

649
00:22:49,501 --> 00:22:51,102
How do you keep doing that?

650
00:22:51,136 --> 00:22:52,370
What?

651
00:22:52,404 --> 00:22:54,105
Just saying things that she'd say,

652
00:22:54,139 --> 00:22:56,007
thinking things that she would...

653
00:22:57,309 --> 00:22:59,343
I guess...

654
00:22:59,378 --> 00:23:01,278
we're a lot alike.

655
00:23:03,849 --> 00:23:04,915
[ Tapping ]

656
00:23:05,984 --> 00:23:07,284
Excuse me.

657
00:23:10,188 --> 00:23:11,255
Where's the fire?

658
00:23:11,289 --> 00:23:12,757
No fire.

659
00:23:12,791 --> 00:23:15,693
I just wanted to let you know that
the house you rent... it sold.

660
00:23:15,727 --> 00:23:17,595
Guess who's the new landlord.

661
00:23:17,629 --> 00:23:18,929
Oh, my God.

662
00:23:18,964 --> 00:23:20,998
You bought my house?!

663
00:23:21,033 --> 00:23:22,933
I had no choice.

664
00:23:22,968 --> 00:23:25,369
Well, I will move. I'll rent a new house.

665
00:23:25,404 --> 00:23:26,904
[ Inhales sharply ]

666
00:23:26,938 --> 00:23:28,072
I'll buy that one, too.

667
00:23:28,106 --> 00:23:30,274
I've got deep pockets,
and I'm very motivated.

668
00:23:30,308 --> 00:23:33,711
Just so you know, even
a landlord has to give notice.

669
00:23:33,745 --> 00:23:36,614
So if you show up uninvited,
I'll call the cops.

670
00:23:36,648 --> 00:23:38,315
Am I interrupting?

671
00:23:38,350 --> 00:23:40,351
Nope. We're done.

672
00:23:40,385 --> 00:23:41,752
I spoke to the D.A.'s office.

673
00:23:41,787 --> 00:23:44,321
They found Sam's birth mother at
a halfway house in the valley.

674
00:23:46,058 --> 00:23:47,925
I don't know what you're after.

675
00:23:47,959 --> 00:23:49,727
Police already talked to me.

676
00:23:49,761 --> 00:23:51,595
They told you that they found your son?

677
00:23:51,630 --> 00:23:52,763
Mm-hmm.

678
00:23:52,798 --> 00:23:54,198
Have you... have you spoken with him yet?

679
00:23:54,232 --> 00:23:55,933
No.

680
00:23:55,967 --> 00:23:59,403
I... can't... imagine.

681
00:23:59,438 --> 00:24:01,505
I mean, it's been 15 years.

682
00:24:01,540 --> 00:24:03,040
This must be really overwhelming.

683
00:24:03,075 --> 00:24:04,909
What am I supposed to do with him?

684
00:24:04,943 --> 00:24:08,045
I mean, I... I can't take care of him.

685
00:24:09,681 --> 00:24:11,449
You know, I...

686
00:24:11,483 --> 00:24:14,085
Vicki, what can you tell me

687
00:24:14,119 --> 00:24:17,788
about the day Sam... Adam... went missing?

688
00:24:17,823 --> 00:24:20,491
I was...

689
00:24:20,525 --> 00:24:22,727
- living with a guy at the time.
- Mm-hmm.

690
00:24:22,761 --> 00:24:24,161
- We were both high.
- Okay.

691
00:24:24,196 --> 00:24:26,664
He... he was dealing in the east,

692
00:24:26,698 --> 00:24:29,333
and he had to go see a guy
who had ripped him off.

693
00:24:29,367 --> 00:24:30,935
And you had your baby with you?

694
00:24:30,969 --> 00:24:32,803
[ Voice breaking ]
I must have.

695
00:24:32,838 --> 00:24:36,674
There was a fight...

696
00:24:36,708 --> 00:24:40,377
and gunshots, so I ran.

697
00:24:40,412 --> 00:24:41,912
I passed out.

698
00:24:41,947 --> 00:24:43,047
[ Sighs ]

699
00:24:43,081 --> 00:24:44,115
Okay.

700
00:24:44,149 --> 00:24:45,216
It's okay. It's okay.

701
00:24:45,250 --> 00:24:49,954
According to the paperwork,
several days went by

702
00:24:49,988 --> 00:24:52,656
before your baby was reported missing,

703
00:24:52,691 --> 00:24:55,493
and it was actually your
grandmother who made the call.

704
00:24:55,527 --> 00:24:59,230
She used to tell me I had
no business being a mother,

705
00:24:59,264 --> 00:25:02,600
and s... she was right.

706
00:25:02,634 --> 00:25:04,068
[ Sobbing ]

707
00:25:04,102 --> 00:25:06,537
You know what my mom
always used to tell me?

708
00:25:06,571 --> 00:25:09,006
That her only job as a mother

709
00:25:09,040 --> 00:25:10,975
was to make sure I grew up loved.

710
00:25:11,009 --> 00:25:13,010
Your son and his 9-year-old sister

711
00:25:13,044 --> 00:25:15,246
are about to be thrown into the system.

712
00:25:15,280 --> 00:25:17,214
They're about to lose
everyone that they love.

713
00:25:17,249 --> 00:25:18,749
I wish I could help.

714
00:25:18,784 --> 00:25:19,683
Okay.

715
00:25:19,718 --> 00:25:20,885
In court tomorrow,

716
00:25:20,919 --> 00:25:23,687
they're gonna ask you
what happened back then.

717
00:25:23,722 --> 00:25:26,590
And it sounds like your memory is hazy.

718
00:25:26,625 --> 00:25:27,992
Is that fair?

719
00:25:28,026 --> 00:25:29,727
Well, I suppose so.

720
00:25:29,761 --> 00:25:33,564
So, is it possible
that you asked Detective Forman

721
00:25:33,598 --> 00:25:35,933
to take care of your baby?

722
00:25:36,935 --> 00:25:38,335
Why would I do that?

723
00:25:38,370 --> 00:25:40,604
No, just, is... is it possible?

724
00:25:40,639 --> 00:25:42,006
What are you saying?

725
00:25:43,508 --> 00:25:48,379
I'm saying that if you can allow
for that possibility,

726
00:25:48,413 --> 00:25:51,248
it could keep a family together.

727
00:25:52,717 --> 00:25:55,753
And that is how you can help your son.

728
00:26:02,027 --> 00:26:03,160
[ Sighs ]

729
00:26:03,195 --> 00:26:04,662
Maybe Jane is right.

730
00:26:04,696 --> 00:26:07,164
Maybe I'm not the kind of person
to start a business.

731
00:26:07,199 --> 00:26:10,734
No, no, no! That's what my mom
would call "stinkin' thinkin'."

732
00:26:10,769 --> 00:26:13,337
For the first time since I gave up acting,

733
00:26:13,371 --> 00:26:16,674
I finally feel like my life
has a direction, a meaning.

734
00:26:16,708 --> 00:26:19,677
We don't need Jane
to help us start a business.

735
00:26:19,711 --> 00:26:22,313
You and me, we'll come up with the money.

736
00:26:22,347 --> 00:26:23,480
We will?

737
00:26:23,515 --> 00:26:25,683
Yeah. I've got like $5,000.
I'll go all-in.

738
00:26:25,717 --> 00:26:27,751
You know, I have about the same amount

739
00:26:27,786 --> 00:26:29,386
left over from my TV show.

740
00:26:29,421 --> 00:26:31,722
Okay, there you go... between you and me,

741
00:26:31,756 --> 00:26:33,824
we can lease kitchen space,
we can get supplies.

742
00:26:33,859 --> 00:26:36,961
Well, it's every penny I have.

743
00:26:36,995 --> 00:26:39,196
What if it doesn't work out?

744
00:26:39,231 --> 00:26:40,664
What if it does?

745
00:26:43,602 --> 00:26:45,169
As a member of the EVK board,

746
00:26:45,203 --> 00:26:47,004
would you say that Elliot Rollins

747
00:26:47,038 --> 00:26:48,706
dictated all strategic planning?

748
00:26:48,740 --> 00:26:51,041
- No.
- Did he ever bypass company by-laws?

749
00:26:51,076 --> 00:26:52,443
Absolutely not.

750
00:26:52,477 --> 00:26:55,079
- Make unilateral decisions?
- Not a single one.

751
00:26:55,113 --> 00:26:58,515
Hire or fire corporate officers
without board approval?

752
00:26:58,550 --> 00:27:01,285
By-laws were followed to a "T."

753
00:27:02,687 --> 00:27:03,754
Thank you.

754
00:27:06,024 --> 00:27:07,291
We have nothing.

755
00:27:07,325 --> 00:27:08,359
We'll scour the minutes.

756
00:27:08,393 --> 00:27:10,327
We have a half dozen
more officers to depose.

757
00:27:10,362 --> 00:27:11,528
This was a huge mistake...

758
00:27:11,563 --> 00:27:13,864
I mean, the fines
they're gonna levy against us?

759
00:27:13,899 --> 00:27:14,899
Kim...

760
00:27:14,933 --> 00:27:16,634
Because of my crazy dad.

761
00:27:16,668 --> 00:27:19,536
[ Sighs ]
I'm gonna take a break.

762
00:27:22,874 --> 00:27:25,509
[ Sighs ]

763
00:27:25,543 --> 00:27:28,312
[ Breathes heavily ]

764
00:27:41,593 --> 00:27:44,628
This is a $900 Morgel faucet.

765
00:27:44,663 --> 00:27:46,063
You have them in all six restrooms

766
00:27:46,097 --> 00:27:47,598
at EVK corporate headquarters.

767
00:27:47,632 --> 00:27:48,966
Do you recognize it?

768
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:50,968
Of course I do. I chose it.

769
00:27:51,002 --> 00:27:53,337
Are you also aware
that this very same fixture

770
00:27:53,371 --> 00:27:55,439
is in the kitchen of your Bel Air home?

771
00:27:55,473 --> 00:27:58,008
I happen to like the faucet.
It's not a crime.

772
00:27:58,043 --> 00:27:59,610
No. It's not.

773
00:27:59,644 --> 00:28:02,346
But using company funds
to decorate your house is.

774
00:28:02,380 --> 00:28:03,981
That's an outrageous charge!

775
00:28:04,015 --> 00:28:05,916
I completely agree... unless it's true.

776
00:28:05,951 --> 00:28:07,017
Is it true?

777
00:28:09,454 --> 00:28:10,187
[ Beep ]

778
00:28:10,221 --> 00:28:11,755
Exhibit "A"...

779
00:28:11,790 --> 00:28:15,225
receipts showing EVK purchased
12 Morgel faucets.

780
00:28:15,260 --> 00:28:18,262
Exhibit "B"... photos showing six faucets

781
00:28:18,296 --> 00:28:19,530
in EVK corporate headquarters

782
00:28:19,564 --> 00:28:22,366
and another six
in Mr. Rollins' Bel Air home.

783
00:28:23,068 --> 00:28:23,934
May I continue?

784
00:28:23,969 --> 00:28:25,235
Absolutely. I'm riveted.

785
00:28:25,270 --> 00:28:28,372
Exhibit "C"...
receipts showing EVK purchased

786
00:28:28,406 --> 00:28:31,075
2,700 square feet
of Italian marble flooring.

787
00:28:31,109 --> 00:28:34,578
Exhibit "D"...
an "Architectural Times" spread

788
00:28:34,612 --> 00:28:38,082
showing Mr. Rollins' refurbished
his Florida estate with...

789
00:28:38,116 --> 00:28:39,383
you want to guess?

790
00:28:39,417 --> 00:28:40,851
Italian marble?

791
00:28:40,885 --> 00:28:43,454
Yep... 2,700 square feet.

792
00:28:43,488 --> 00:28:45,422
Objection, Your Honor.
This is civil court.

793
00:28:45,457 --> 00:28:47,725
These allegations are irrelevant
to the matter at hand.

794
00:28:47,759 --> 00:28:50,894
Oh, that's why the
U.S. Attorneys' Office is here.

795
00:28:53,631 --> 00:28:55,299
If you add up all the money

796
00:28:55,333 --> 00:28:58,002
Elliot Rollins liberated
from his corporate account

797
00:28:58,036 --> 00:29:00,838
to furnish his collection of
homes, it amounts to, uh...

798
00:29:00,872 --> 00:29:02,339
what was that number, again?

799
00:29:02,374 --> 00:29:03,907
Grand larceny.

800
00:29:03,942 --> 00:29:05,709
That's it.

801
00:29:10,382 --> 00:29:12,349
Jane, please tell me
you've got something...

802
00:29:12,384 --> 00:29:14,852
that my sister's not gonna
grow up in the foster system.

803
00:29:14,886 --> 00:29:16,653
Okay, Sam, listen,

804
00:29:16,688 --> 00:29:18,155
all of the facts are against us.

805
00:29:18,189 --> 00:29:21,358
Now, I... I'm not making any promises...

806
00:29:21,393 --> 00:29:22,259
But?

807
00:29:22,293 --> 00:29:23,927
But I talked to your birth mom.

808
00:29:23,962 --> 00:29:27,765
And... I'm working on something.

809
00:29:27,799 --> 00:29:31,101
And it... it is a long shot, okay?

810
00:29:31,136 --> 00:29:32,302
[ Door opens ]
But...

811
00:29:32,337 --> 00:29:33,737
I couldn't keep them out.

812
00:29:33,772 --> 00:29:35,506
- Jane Bingum?
- Yes?

813
00:29:35,540 --> 00:29:37,574
You're under arrest for witness
tampering and suborning of perjury.

814
00:29:37,609 --> 00:29:38,809
I... I don't understand.

815
00:29:38,843 --> 00:29:39,643
What's going on?

816
00:29:39,677 --> 00:29:41,178
Did you speak with Vicki Gates?

817
00:29:41,212 --> 00:29:43,781
As I'm entitled to as...

818
00:29:43,815 --> 00:29:45,783
And did you instruct her
to lie on the stand?

819
00:29:45,817 --> 00:29:48,852
No. No. No. It wasn't...
it wasn't... wasn't like that.

820
00:29:48,887 --> 00:29:50,254
Wasn't like what?

821
00:29:50,288 --> 00:29:52,656
I am exercising my right to remain silent.

822
00:29:52,690 --> 00:29:54,091
Cuff her.

823
00:29:54,125 --> 00:29:56,060
[ Police radio chatter ]

824
00:29:56,094 --> 00:29:57,661
[ Handcuffs click ]

825
00:30:02,189 --> 00:30:03,290
[ Whistles ]

826
00:30:03,324 --> 00:30:05,058
Good news... you're getting sprung.

827
00:30:05,092 --> 00:30:07,694
- I haven't even been arraigned.
- No, charges were dropped.

828
00:30:07,728 --> 00:30:09,663
Apparently, Vicki Gates left
town without alerting the D.A.

829
00:30:09,697 --> 00:30:10,697
They had no choice.

830
00:30:11,766 --> 00:30:14,801
So, I guess you heard the charges?

831
00:30:15,937 --> 00:30:20,140
Witness tampering, suborning perjury.

832
00:30:20,174 --> 00:30:22,876
Go ahead. I am ready for my lecture.

833
00:30:22,910 --> 00:30:24,811
No. The world's not black and white, Jane.

834
00:30:24,845 --> 00:30:26,246
It's why I joined the bench.

835
00:30:26,280 --> 00:30:29,282
I was tired of appearing in front
of judges who thought it was.

836
00:30:29,317 --> 00:30:30,650
- Really?
- Mm-hmm.

837
00:30:30,685 --> 00:30:32,552
I always thought it was
just 'cause you liked the fact

838
00:30:32,586 --> 00:30:34,321
that people stood up
when you entered the room.

839
00:30:34,355 --> 00:30:36,356
[ Laughs ]

840
00:30:36,390 --> 00:30:38,358
Whatcha looking at?

841
00:30:38,392 --> 00:30:40,760
I'm just taking
a mental picture for later.

842
00:30:40,795 --> 00:30:43,496
You know, a woman behind bars...
it's kind of hot.

843
00:30:43,531 --> 00:30:45,031
[ Laughs ]

844
00:30:45,066 --> 00:30:46,333
Is it?

845
00:30:48,636 --> 00:30:50,203
So, I packed up all my gear

846
00:30:50,237 --> 00:30:52,272
and slipped the key right under his mat.

847
00:30:52,306 --> 00:30:54,240
Well, it is not his mat anymore.

848
00:30:54,275 --> 00:30:56,743
The feds seized all six of Rollins' homes

849
00:30:56,777 --> 00:30:58,945
in their criminal investigation.

850
00:30:58,980 --> 00:31:01,815
And the best part...

851
00:31:03,084 --> 00:31:04,884
Uh-huh. What's this?

852
00:31:04,919 --> 00:31:06,319
A notice of impending settlement.

853
00:31:06,354 --> 00:31:09,055
They're cutting you a check
for your 34 grand,

854
00:31:09,090 --> 00:31:10,790
and the rest of his personal fortune

855
00:31:10,825 --> 00:31:13,893
will be spent reimbursing
every employee he ripped off.

856
00:31:13,928 --> 00:31:16,930
Pickles, you're a miracle worker.

857
00:31:16,964 --> 00:31:18,098
[ Laughs ]

858
00:31:18,132 --> 00:31:19,332
Yes, she is.

859
00:31:19,367 --> 00:31:20,767
[ Laughs ]

860
00:31:20,801 --> 00:31:22,035
It's been a pleasure meeting you, Larry.

861
00:31:22,069 --> 00:31:23,370
I've been hearing about you for... years.

862
00:31:23,404 --> 00:31:26,506
Mr. Parker, you're an excellent liar, sir.

863
00:31:27,441 --> 00:31:29,976
But I appreciate the thought.

864
00:31:30,011 --> 00:31:31,978
So, uh, how long you two been a couple?

865
00:31:32,013 --> 00:31:34,014
- Oh.
- What's that?

866
00:31:34,048 --> 00:31:35,281
[ Chuckles nervously ]
We're not... no.

867
00:31:35,316 --> 00:31:36,416
Ah, come on.

868
00:31:36,450 --> 00:31:38,818
Let me walk her down the aisle
already, will you?

869
00:31:38,853 --> 00:31:40,620
Okay, why don't I... I just walk you out?

870
00:31:40,654 --> 00:31:41,621
[ Chuckles nervously ]

871
00:31:41,655 --> 00:31:43,256
[ Laughs ]

872
00:31:47,028 --> 00:31:48,328
Sam?

873
00:31:48,362 --> 00:31:50,163
How did you know I'd be out of jail?

874
00:31:50,197 --> 00:31:52,465
I had a feeling
the charges wouldn't hold up.

875
00:31:53,401 --> 00:31:54,567
What did you do?

876
00:31:54,602 --> 00:31:56,503
I found Vicki,

877
00:31:56,537 --> 00:31:58,938
asked her what it would take
for her to go away,

878
00:31:58,973 --> 00:32:00,507
and I cut her a check.

879
00:32:00,541 --> 00:32:01,841
Sam.

880
00:32:01,876 --> 00:32:04,210
Jane, my dad needs you out of jail.

881
00:32:04,245 --> 00:32:06,846
Please, please don't get your hopes up.

882
00:32:06,881 --> 00:32:08,348
This happened 15 years ago.

883
00:32:08,382 --> 00:32:10,483
You can't argue statute
of limitations or something?

884
00:32:10,518 --> 00:32:12,619
There is no statute
of limitations on kidnapping.

885
00:32:12,653 --> 00:32:15,789
What about termination of parental rights?

886
00:32:15,823 --> 00:32:17,290
It wasn't a kidnapping because Vicki Gates

887
00:32:17,324 --> 00:32:19,359
already de facto terminated
her parental rights

888
00:32:19,393 --> 00:32:21,161
by abandoning her child in a drug den.

889
00:32:21,195 --> 00:32:22,562
An emotional argument.

890
00:32:24,465 --> 00:32:26,132
That's worth a try.

891
00:32:27,635 --> 00:32:29,803
16-year-old Sam Forman...

892
00:32:29,837 --> 00:32:32,572
a loving brother, a devoted son,

893
00:32:32,606 --> 00:32:33,907
a straight-A student,

894
00:32:33,941 --> 00:32:37,243
and not to mention C.E.O. of
a multimillion-dollar company.

895
00:32:37,278 --> 00:32:39,312
And if it weren't for my client,

896
00:32:39,346 --> 00:32:40,447
it is quite possible

897
00:32:40,481 --> 00:32:42,549
that Sam Forman
wouldn't even be alive today.

898
00:32:42,583 --> 00:32:43,750
Calls for speculation.

899
00:32:43,784 --> 00:32:46,252
Detective Forman tried
to go through proper channels,

900
00:32:46,287 --> 00:32:47,954
and when he got no response,

901
00:32:47,988 --> 00:32:50,490
he did everything right by this young man.

902
00:32:51,826 --> 00:32:54,294
Sometimes, you can be right
and still be wrong.

903
00:32:54,328 --> 00:32:57,564
Without a legal rationale,
I simply can't do it.

904
00:33:05,539 --> 00:33:08,141
Statute of limitations, Your Honor.

905
00:33:08,175 --> 00:33:11,377
Your Honor, there is no statute
of limitations on kidnapping.

906
00:33:11,412 --> 00:33:14,347
I agree, but there is
a statute of limitations

907
00:33:14,381 --> 00:33:16,549
on the reporting and prosecuting
of a kidnapping.

908
00:33:16,584 --> 00:33:19,185
Per section 802-A
of California Penal Code,

909
00:33:19,220 --> 00:33:21,321
the state is required
to prosecute a kidnapping

910
00:33:21,355 --> 00:33:23,456
within one year
of the crime being reported.

911
00:33:23,491 --> 00:33:24,591
Ah!

912
00:33:24,625 --> 00:33:27,260
Your Honor, this crime
was reported 48 hours ago.

913
00:33:27,294 --> 00:33:30,196
Oh, actually,
you're off by about 15 years.

914
00:33:30,231 --> 00:33:31,397
And we contend

915
00:33:31,432 --> 00:33:34,701
that any number of L.A.
police officers were aware

916
00:33:34,735 --> 00:33:37,137
that detective Forman
brought the baby home

917
00:33:37,171 --> 00:33:40,073
from the crime scene 15 years ago.

918
00:33:40,107 --> 00:33:41,374
And this means

919
00:33:41,408 --> 00:33:45,778
he has remained uncharged
and unprosecuted for 15 years.

920
00:33:45,813 --> 00:33:47,447
Can you prove that?

921
00:33:47,481 --> 00:33:49,349
Let me try.

922
00:33:50,451 --> 00:33:53,453
Are there any sworn L.A.P.D.
officers who were present

923
00:33:53,487 --> 00:33:56,022
when detective Forman found the child?

924
00:34:09,370 --> 00:34:11,938
Are there any sworn L.A.P.D. officers

925
00:34:11,972 --> 00:34:14,007
who have known for more than a year

926
00:34:14,041 --> 00:34:17,010
that detective Forman
raised this boy as his own?

927
00:34:33,194 --> 00:34:34,861
Jane, thank you so much.

928
00:34:34,895 --> 00:34:36,496
You couldn't be more welcome.

929
00:34:42,169 --> 00:34:43,803
Go. Talk to her.

930
00:34:49,977 --> 00:34:51,077
Here.

931
00:34:51,111 --> 00:34:53,413
This is yours. I gave this to you.

932
00:34:53,447 --> 00:34:54,447
No, I... I don't want it.

933
00:34:54,481 --> 00:34:57,050
I... I thought that I did, but no.

934
00:34:57,084 --> 00:34:59,419
So what do you want?

935
00:34:59,453 --> 00:35:02,255
What any mother wants...

936
00:35:02,289 --> 00:35:06,259
to see that you're happy,
to know that you're loved.

937
00:35:09,496 --> 00:35:10,463
Daddy!

938
00:35:10,497 --> 00:35:11,564
Hey!

939
00:35:11,599 --> 00:35:12,465
Oh, daddy!

940
00:35:12,499 --> 00:35:14,567
Ohh!

941
00:35:14,602 --> 00:35:16,202
Thank him for me, okay?

942
00:35:16,237 --> 00:35:18,638
I will.

943
00:35:20,908 --> 00:35:22,075
Hey, dad.

944
00:35:22,109 --> 00:35:23,476
Hey, buddy.

945
00:35:23,510 --> 00:35:24,544
Sorry.

946
00:35:32,553 --> 00:35:34,487
Victory celebration tonight? 9:00?

947
00:35:34,521 --> 00:35:35,388
Yeah.

948
00:35:35,422 --> 00:35:37,590
Say, uh, Founders?

949
00:35:37,625 --> 00:35:39,459
Founders. Isn't... isn't that where...

950
00:35:39,493 --> 00:35:40,927
Yeah, it's where Deb and I
used to hang out.

951
00:35:40,961 --> 00:35:41,928
Oh.

952
00:35:41,962 --> 00:35:43,696
There's some stuff we should talk about.

953
00:35:43,731 --> 00:35:44,797
Okay.

954
00:35:44,832 --> 00:35:46,299
See you there.

955
00:35:46,333 --> 00:35:47,700
Okay.

956
00:35:55,209 --> 00:35:58,478
Stacy, I'm really sorry.

957
00:35:58,512 --> 00:36:00,947
I mean, I really... I didn't
mean to be unsupportive.

958
00:36:00,981 --> 00:36:03,883
No, I totally overreacted.

959
00:36:03,917 --> 00:36:05,318
I understand that now.

960
00:36:05,352 --> 00:36:07,120
I talked it over with Luke,

961
00:36:07,154 --> 00:36:09,222
[ voice breaking ]
and I'm sorry.

962
00:36:09,256 --> 00:36:10,723
I'm sorry.

963
00:36:10,758 --> 00:36:13,126
[ Chuckles ]

964
00:36:13,160 --> 00:36:15,261
You talked it over with who?

965
00:36:15,296 --> 00:36:16,195
Luke: Me.

966
00:36:16,230 --> 00:36:19,465
Uh, Jane, meet Luke, our new landlord.

967
00:36:19,500 --> 00:36:20,533
You're gonna love him.

968
00:36:20,567 --> 00:36:21,567
Oh, we've met.

969
00:36:21,602 --> 00:36:24,203
He's measuring
for a new convection oven...

970
00:36:24,238 --> 00:36:25,905
the same one Rachael Ray uses.

971
00:36:25,939 --> 00:36:27,106
Wow. Really?

972
00:36:27,141 --> 00:36:28,975
Yep. That's the kind of landlord I am.

973
00:36:29,009 --> 00:36:30,043
Oh.

974
00:36:30,077 --> 00:36:32,045
I explained to Stacy
that I'm required by law

975
00:36:32,079 --> 00:36:34,647
to give you 24 hours' notice
before coming in.

976
00:36:34,682 --> 00:36:36,149
- Mm-hmm. But I waived it.
- What?!

977
00:36:36,183 --> 00:36:37,216
She is such a sweetheart.

978
00:36:37,251 --> 00:36:38,718
Well, I just told him

979
00:36:38,752 --> 00:36:40,687
he could come in and out as needed.

980
00:36:40,721 --> 00:36:41,921
I mean, that's okay with you, right?

981
00:36:41,955 --> 00:36:44,590
If you've already said yes,
then I don't have...

982
00:36:44,625 --> 00:36:46,492
See, told ya... no problem.

983
00:36:46,527 --> 00:36:47,560
Yes.

984
00:36:47,594 --> 00:36:49,462
Well, I just came home to freshen up.

985
00:36:49,496 --> 00:36:51,931
I'm meeting Grayson for drinks.

986
00:36:51,965 --> 00:36:54,867
He said he had something
important to talk to me about.

987
00:36:54,902 --> 00:36:56,302
Really?

988
00:36:56,337 --> 00:36:57,603
Really.

989
00:36:57,638 --> 00:36:58,438
Really?

990
00:37:00,207 --> 00:37:01,607
Really.

991
00:37:12,886 --> 00:37:15,054
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

992
00:37:15,089 --> 00:37:17,256
[ Sighs ]

993
00:37:17,291 --> 00:37:19,559
Luke, what are you doing here?

994
00:37:19,593 --> 00:37:22,028
You have to shut it down, Jane.
Grayson can't know.

995
00:37:22,062 --> 00:37:23,763
I don't know what you're talking about.

996
00:37:23,797 --> 00:37:25,398
All these questions he's been asking...

997
00:37:25,432 --> 00:37:26,933
"do you believe in reincarnation?"

998
00:37:26,967 --> 00:37:29,402
"Did you know that Deb died
the same day you got shot?"

999
00:37:29,436 --> 00:37:31,137
What do you think he's getting at?

1000
00:37:31,171 --> 00:37:32,438
You tell me, Luke.

1001
00:37:32,473 --> 00:37:33,840
He's wondering if you could be

1002
00:37:33,874 --> 00:37:35,608
the long-deceased love of his life.

1003
00:37:36,643 --> 00:37:38,211
And what if I want him to know?

1004
00:37:38,245 --> 00:37:40,646
He can't know what you want him to know.

1005
00:37:42,282 --> 00:37:43,816
There will be consequences.

1006
00:37:43,851 --> 00:37:45,885
You remember what happened the
last time you almost told him?

1007
00:37:45,919 --> 00:37:47,520
He got hit by a car, Jane.

1008
00:37:47,554 --> 00:37:49,288
Don't do that.

1009
00:37:49,323 --> 00:37:50,990
If you confirm what he already suspects...

1010
00:37:51,024 --> 00:37:53,092
What am I supposed to do?

1011
00:37:53,127 --> 00:37:55,361
Put Deb behind you.

1012
00:37:56,730 --> 00:37:59,866
Put Grayson behind you.

1013
00:37:59,900 --> 00:38:01,167
Move on as Jane.

1014
00:38:02,803 --> 00:38:04,370
You're with Owen now, right?

1015
00:38:05,739 --> 00:38:07,340
Yes.

1016
00:38:09,443 --> 00:38:10,810
Shut it down.

1017
00:38:14,047 --> 00:38:16,082
[ Sighs ]

1018
00:38:17,918 --> 00:38:19,519
Hey, man, play a song for me?

1019
00:38:19,553 --> 00:38:20,620
Absolutely. Whatcha thinking?

1020
00:38:20,654 --> 00:38:22,121
"Unchained Melody."

1021
00:38:22,156 --> 00:38:24,357
All right. Righteous Brothers,
uh, from the movie "Ghost."

1022
00:38:24,391 --> 00:38:26,726
Yeah. Yeah, my girlfriend
used to love the movie.

1023
00:38:26,760 --> 00:38:29,128
Ever since we saw it
and the song would come on,

1024
00:38:29,163 --> 00:38:30,897
she would just burst into tears.

1025
00:38:30,931 --> 00:38:32,598
[ "Unchained Melody" playing ]

1026
00:38:35,002 --> 00:38:36,035
Thanks for coming.

1027
00:38:36,069 --> 00:38:39,439
Well, I couldn't let you celebrate alone.

1028
00:38:39,473 --> 00:38:40,807
Well, like I said,

1029
00:38:40,841 --> 00:38:43,309
there's something
I want to talk to you about.

1030
00:38:43,343 --> 00:38:44,343
What?

1031
00:38:44,378 --> 00:38:45,411
[ Clears throat ]

1032
00:38:45,446 --> 00:38:46,746
♪ My darling

1033
00:38:46,780 --> 00:38:50,716
♪ I've hungered for your touch ♪

1034
00:38:50,751 --> 00:38:51,818
Listen.

1035
00:38:51,852 --> 00:38:53,085
What?

1036
00:38:53,120 --> 00:38:55,388
This song.

1037
00:38:55,422 --> 00:38:57,523
It's heartbreaking, right?

1038
00:38:57,558 --> 00:39:00,193
Really? This song?

1039
00:39:00,227 --> 00:39:01,394
Mm.

1040
00:39:01,428 --> 00:39:03,896
Yeah, it's from the movie
"Ghost." You know it.

1041
00:39:03,931 --> 00:39:05,431
Oh, yeah. I'm just not a fan.

1042
00:39:05,466 --> 00:39:07,600
I don't believe it.

1043
00:39:07,634 --> 00:39:10,369
No, really. It's so sappy.

1044
00:39:10,404 --> 00:39:13,072
I mean, listen to those lyrics.
"I hunger for your touch."

1045
00:39:13,106 --> 00:39:14,607
[ Laughing ]
